Over the years, many have soured on onchain governance due to its widespread inefficacy. 

Imo this is largely due to under-investment in tooling and contributors, rather than a fundamental property of the medium

Yeah i'm basically saying we don't have enough DAO tooling lol

If you look at the DAO with the largest treasuries, most of the work (at least by value) is done via comp governor bravo or similar products from maker & aave.

so it's pretty clear that if you're going to try to improve the operational efficacy of daos, you need to start there

then if you dig into gov bravo – it's apparent that there is a clear problems: the tokens are not help by people you want to be governing.

the solution is also clear: token holders can delegate their vote to more engaged and qualified voters

but getting them to do that is hard
So that's where we're starting: building an app that puts forward the best delegates and gives them a platform to advocate for their views

Great move from Safe DAO:

1. protects the community from airdrop farmers
2. puts more tokens (and voting power) in the hands of skilled participants
3. creates a very nice incentive to participate in the community https://i.imgur.com/YG94Rkd.jpg

Smol governance idea: 

Voters get a budget to drive a metric over a time period, fund builders out of that budget, and get paid the remainder of the budget if metrics are met at the end of the period.

a little like uma kpi options, but specfically targeted towards creating better incentives for voters

Perhaps controversial take: 

Labs teams should aim to retire post token issuance and governance initialization for their protocol

BDFL is a very poor pattern for growing a real decentralized ecosystem.

Also teams just don’t have the incentive to stay after the inevitable 50% dilution from token issuance

Things get awkward when labs teams have no revenue, have <20% of token supply with which they can’t really vote but still insist on keeping on.

The more they do, the weirder the incentive alignment becomes

You kinda have to decide whether you want to be centralized trad startup, or an open source project with a token. Trying to operate as the former while having the structure of the latter is just cringe
“Labs team retirement considered bullish”

Yeah this is a good pattern. Aave and Comp both have some versions of this where they have special allowances that reduce friction for teams making param tuning proposals.

Both labs have also stepped back and let 3rd parties run / develop the protocol on a day to day basis. If they hadn't things would be more awks
For active nouns folks who aren't voting with Agora – what could we do better?

imo there are pretty much like only 3 types of protocol governance raison d'être
